00:07:56,050 --> 00:08:15,325
As Linda mentioned, Niche Engineering has been retained by the City of Medford to perform engineering design for the proposed shared-use path connection and timber boardwalk to provide a safe and accessible connection between McDonald Park on the north side of Route 28 and Station Landing located to the south.

63
00:08:16,526 --> 00:08:22,471
I would first like to provide a history of the project and how we got to this point in the project design process.

64
00:08:23,452 --> 00:08:32,739
The City of Medford received a Massachusetts Gaming Commission Transportation Planning Grant to initiate the design of the proposed project in July of 2019.

65
00:08:33,479 --> 00:08:42,286
In March of 2020, the City of Medford initiated the design process with Niche Engineering as their design consultant.

66
00:08:43,487 --> 00:08:51,332
Niche Engineering prepared a preliminary design and submitted plans to the DCR and the City of Medford for review in September of 2020.

67
00:08:53,335 --> 00:09:03,621
The project was approved by the Project Review Committee in January of 2021, which made the project eligible for Transportation Improvement Program funding.

68
00:09:04,662 --> 00:09:12,787
Niche Engineering prepared 25% design plans and submitted plans to MassDOT for review in February of 2022.

69
00:09:13,087 --> 00:09:22,533
The project was initiated by the City of Medford,

70
00:09:22,933 --> 00:09:35,898
with assistance from the Mystic River Watershed Association and the Massachusetts Gaming Commission to provide a safe and accessible connection between existing paths on the north and south sides of Route 28.

71
00:09:36,098 --> 00:09:42,160
The proposed connection had been previously identified on several regional plans.

72
00:09:42,921 --> 00:09:51,984
The Metropolitan Area Planning Council Regional Greenway Network, the Mystic Greenways Initiative by the Mystic River Watershed Association,

73
00:09:52,741 --> 00:09:59,745
and the 2009 Mystic River Master Plan created by the Massachusetts Department of Conservation and Recreation.

74
00:10:06,009 --> 00:10:12,953
Project stakeholders have identified several objectives that we want to accomplish through the development of this important project.

75
00:10:14,134 --> 00:10:16,795
The following goals have been established for the project.

76
00:10:17,555 --> 00:10:20,017
Improve bicycle and pedestrian safety,

77
00:10:20,882 --> 00:10:38,356
provide a safer connection between McDonald Park to station landing, minimize environmental impacts, create an accessible shared-use path connection, and connect the shared-use path to the new bike lanes recently installed along Route 28.

78
00:10:42,919 --> 00:10:50,045
During the early stages of the design process, several alternatives were considered and presented to the project stakeholders.

79
00:10:51,483 --> 00:11:08,272
Alternatives were developed to review various path alignments in order to evaluate impacts to existing trees and vegetation along the Mystic River and determine potential increases to impervious area that would be created through the construction of new asphalt path connections.

80
00:11:13,935 --> 00:11:19,058
Through close coordination with the various project stakeholders, a preferred alternative was determined

81
00:11:19,374 --> 00:11:22,096
to be advanced to the 25% design level.

82
00:11:23,437 --> 00:11:35,704
The preferred alternative was selected to provide path connections for pedestrians and bicyclists to McDonald Park, Station Landing, the new bike lanes on Route 28, and existing sidewalks.

83
00:11:36,825 --> 00:11:45,390
A new timber boardwalk is proposed to connect points north and south beneath the existing Felsway Route 28 bridge over the Mystic River.

84
00:11:46,455 --> 00:11:55,397
It was also determined that there's a desire to provide two overlooks along the new boardwalk, one looking south along the river and the other looking to the north.

85
00:11:56,338 --> 00:11:59,758
The sketch presented shows the preferred circulation plan.

86
00:12:00,659 --> 00:12:07,501
The orange lines represent the new shared use path alignment designed to accommodate both bicycles and pedestrians.

87
00:12:08,481 --> 00:12:13,102
The blue lines show proposed connections for pedestrians to McDonald Park

88
00:12:13,526 --> 00:12:16,849
and the sidewalks along the Mystic River Bridge and Route 28.

89
00:12:17,990 --> 00:12:26,156
Red lines identify the proposed bicycle connections to and from the new bike lanes along 28 and the shared use path connections.

90
00:12:32,862 --> 00:12:42,710
The design has progressed from the conceptual design phase where the preferred alternative was selected and the preliminary design has advanced to the plans that we are sharing this evening.

91
00:12:43,493 --> 00:12:47,074
The project design is currently at the 25% design level.

92
00:12:49,534 --> 00:12:54,355
Several tasks have been completed in order to get to an approved 25% design.

93
00:12:55,236 --> 00:13:01,317
Niche engineering began the design process by conducting on-the-ground topographic survey of the project area.

94
00:13:02,277 --> 00:13:10,299
Once the project concepts were evaluated and a preferred alignment selected, niche engineering conducted soil borings along the shore

95
00:13:10,941 --> 00:13:15,262
and in the river in order to design the structural elements of the timber boardwalk.

96
00:13:16,562 --> 00:13:24,343
We also coordinated with the various public and private utility companies to develop a design that minimizes impacts to adjacent utilities.

97
00:13:25,944 --> 00:13:31,905
We conducted a permitting analysis to identify environmental permits that will be required to construct the project.

98
00:13:32,805 --> 00:13:39,706
All of these elements were incorporated in the development of the 25% design plans that were submitted to MassDOT.

99
00:13:44,732 --> 00:13:54,418
The new shared-use path connection is designed to accommodate both bicycles and pedestrians and is proposed to be 12 feet wide with grassed shoulders on each side.

100
00:13:55,738 --> 00:14:10,027
One-way bicycle connections to and from the new bike lanes on Route 28 will be six feet wide and pedestrian paths connecting to existing sidewalks will be a minimum of six feet wide and will transition to meet existing sidewalk widths.

101
00:14:11,797 --> 00:14:23,487
The proposed timber boardwalk is designed to mimic the existing boardwalk on the south side of the river in Somerville, and will provide a 12-foot clear width between timber railings on each side.

102
00:14:24,607 --> 00:14:33,975
The timber boardwalk will be supported on structural helical piles, which are installed into the riverbed, which eliminates the need for excavation within the river.

103
00:14:35,096 --> 00:14:39,600
Path lighting is proposed along the new boardwalk and shared-use path connections.

